metadata.name: Ignorance is Bliss #88
metadata.description:
"Ignorance is Bliss" is the second collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

People often argue over things that are not under their control. But why bother? At the end of the day, your opinion won't change anything unless you have the power to accomplish that change. Of course you can say that you are aguing for "The Truth" or "Justice", but what's the point in your bickering if you aren't going to accomplish anything?
But you can go even further than that, you can choose to ignore global problems completely, live in your own world. One who doesn't know of a problem shan't worry about it - thus, ignorance is bliss. 
Is it right or is it wrong? What's the point in arguing over what I wrote if you won't change anything? All you can do is decide for yourself.

metadata.name: Mines #51
metadata.description:
"He found himself wondering at times, especially in the autumn, about the wild lands, and strange visions of mountains that he had never seen came into his dreams"

Mines is an exploration of these mountains of dreams, and the ancient mechanics that shape them. The work of eons, where the landscapes we know rise and fall like ocean waves.

To know them, we must go beneath the mountain.

metadata.name: Complicare #23
metadata.description:
Complicare is my first "still" generative work, and an exercise in minimalism.

Inspired by pioneers like Sol Lewitt and Frank Stella, as well as current fx_hash artists such as Rev Dan Catt and Yazid, this work attempts to balance a diverse visual output with a restricted generative system. I also wanted to focus on honing my abilities to add texture to the digital canvas, taking cues from other great artists on here like William Mapan and Hevey.

Each piece has one of 17 different layouts and one of 6 different color palettes.

Thanks to all of the artists on fx_hash for inspiring me every day to make more art, and particularly to dcarcher for some really insightful artistic perspective and feedback.

metadata.name: ION TRAP #297
metadata.description:
Inside the ION TRAP, reality is suspended. Particles hang motionless, captured in a glowing web of energy that hums with an endless, static resonance. Time has ceased to flow, frozen in a tension where neither motion nor decay is possible. The trap's design reflects the peak of retro-futuristic ambition; crafted to transcend the very limits of nature. It stands as a testament to the brilliance ‚Äî and the final misstep ‚Äî of a civilization that sought to master the fabric of existence, only to unwittingly freeze their world forever.

***

Press ‚¨ÖÔ∏è‚û°Ô∏è to rotate scene.

Press [1/2/4/6/8/0] to change resolution to 1/2/4/6/8/10K along the short edge. 

Press [s] to save a png at the current resolution. Saving at higher resolutions may not work on all browsers (tested: all resolutions work using Safari on an M2 mac. Up to 4K work on Chrome). 

Press [p] to restart the draw animation and initiate download of png frames at current resolution until drawing is complete. Typically generates 500-600 images. Can be assembled into a video / GIF with your software of choice. Recommend doing this at 2K resolution.

100% code generative artwork written in javascript using the p5.js library.

PARAMS:

¬∑WYSIWYG: use minter address as random seed (you get what you see) or use transaction hash (random) default: true.
¬∑WYSIWYG seed: number of minter random seed. (It's not really a seed. Each time it is sent to the $fx.randminter() function, it is done 5 times and the results are sequenced. Aix√≤ gives more flexibility to the minter.)
¬∑max changes: max number of changes (default: random)
¬∑Num. sources: Number of sources (patterns). 1-4, default: random.
¬∑src distribution: Source patterns distribution: rectangles, rows or columns (default: rows)
¬∑src rand size: Size of source patterns: same size (false) (default) / random size (true)
¬∑src density: Density of source patterns. ["low","mid", "high","random"]-> default: random
¬∑src thikness: Thickness of source patterns. ["thin","mid", "thick","random"]-> default: random.
¬∑src only lines: Use only source patterns based on lines (true) / use any type of source pattern (false). Default: false
¬∑allow circles: allow circle as a base shape for changes (default: false)
¬∑pxl invert prob: probability of pixel invertion change. (0.0->0.5)->default: 0.2
¬∑noise prob: probability of noise change. (0.0->1.0)->default: 0.5
¬∑glitch prob: probability of glitch change. (0.0->0.5)->default: 0.2

FEATURES:

¬∑WYSIWYG: It has been minter using minter address (true) or not (false)
¬∑num_of_sources: number of source patterns. (1-4)
¬∑src_same_size: source patterns have the same size (true/false)
¬∑src_distribution: source patterns distribution: rectangles, rows or columns
¬∑num_of_changes: num of changes. (2-24)
¬∑density: density of source patters: low, mid or high.
¬∑thikness: thickness of source patterns: thin, mid or thick.
¬∑only_lines: only lines source patterns (true) or all source patterns (false ) option.
¬∑hasCircle: at least one circle has been used in one change (true/false)
¬∑hasNoise: at least one noise change (true/false)

metadata.name: Pegs In Motion #397
metadata.description:
Pegs In Motion adds a twist to the original PEGS project by adding animation, rotating the pegs to make the string loop around the grid and bring the artwork alive. Forever limited to 500 unique editions on the Tezos blockchain.

Taking inspiration from work by Karl Gerstner, Armin Hofmann, Nick Kuder and Dmitri Cherniak, Pegs In Motion explores the limits of constrained algorithmic variation. Based on the simple, playful idea of wrapping a string across a board of pegs, it shows how endless possibilities can be achieved with just a basic set of rules and a few primary colors. When done right, generative art challenges us to answer fundamental questions around creativity, beauty, and life itself.

metadata.name: The Abstract Truth III #28
metadata.description:
Moir√© patterns meet halftone dots meet cross stitching.

Halftone is a term that can refer to both a technology used in image processing and as the synonym for semitone in music. A jazz musician Oliver Nelson released the album The Blues and the Abstract Truth in 1961. It is considered one of the most significant records of its time. In addition, he wrote Patterns for Improvisation, a hugely popular jazz patterns book. The Moir√© pattern design is on the book's cover.

Look out for the FOMO keyboard key to unlock more variations. 
Press 'P' to pause/unpause the animation.

metadata.name: Country Spirit I #27
metadata.description:
‚ÄúRaoul Pictor cherche son style‚Ä¶‚Äù (Raoul Pictor is looking for his style‚Ä¶) was launched in Saint-Gall, Switzerland, in 1993. It consists of a Mac LC computer, a 12-inch color screen, and an HP 500C printer.
The program presents an animation in which we can observe an artist, Raoul Pictor, working in his studio. He paints, paces while deep in thought, consults books from his library, plays the piano, and enjoys red wine. The sequence of these activities is non-linear. The canvas is seen from behind, resting on the easel in the center of the room. We are unable to see what is being painted. Once his painting is complete, he picks it up and exits through a side door. It is at this moment that the printer springs into action, delivering his unique, dated, and signed work.
This project has been exhibited in numerous exhibitions around the world. Subsequently, a Flash version, "Raoul Pictor Web Studio," was developed to make it available on the internet (2001). In 2013, for its 20th anniversary, an iOS version, "Raoul Pictor Mega Painter," was developed in collaboration with the great Matthieu Cherubini (mchrbn.net). 
In 2023, for its 30th anniversary, an update seemed necessary to continue the adventure on the fx(hash) platform ‚Äì thank you for making all of this possible! The development of this first fx version (‚ÄúCountry Spirit I‚Äù) was greatly enhanced by the wonderful support and expertise of the sha22.art team as well as our friends. Additional collections are now planned for the near future or special events...

[up_arrow], [space bar] : Painter jumps in first part of animation.

[p], [mouse click], [touch screen] : Save the painting when it is displayed.

metadata.name: Chroma Dance #5
metadata.description:
Chroma Dance explores the beauty of simplicity and color. Through gracefully revealed triangles and curated hues, this collection celebrates the elegance found in minimalist shapes. With a harmonious palette and effortless charm, the triangle compositions unite to create a visual enchantment.

Watch the "dance" as your composition rotates at set intervals, presenting it in different views. Once a full 360 degree presentation has completed, the colors will randomly shuffle and the process begins again. A continuous display of geometry and changing color.

Discover special controls in the right-click menu (or double tap on your touch device). You can pause the animation, adjust the hold time between rotations and toggle fullscreen mode. While in fullscreen mode there are additional controls for the presentation of your piece, including options for background color, texture and shadow. Customise the view to suit your display.

Visit the piece directly by clicking the "Open" link, and the menu will include options for downloading quality images of your piece at different sizes. It will download an image of the composition and rotation displayed at the time.

metadata.name: Scaffold #116
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution‚Ä®
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment
